00:03:04.619 --> 00:03:06.312
Just some simple definitions.

00:03:06.312 --> 00:03:07.324
What is a seizure?

00:03:07.324 --> 00:03:09.523
There are actually
three-hour-long symposia

00:03:09.523 --> 00:03:11.021
at the American Epilepsy Society meeting

00:03:11.021 --> 00:03:12.164
about what is a seizure.

00:03:12.164 --> 00:03:13.826
This is still debated,
but for our purposes,

00:03:13.826 --> 00:03:15.884
I think we can come to an agreement

00:03:15.884 --> 00:03:18.866
that it's a transient occurrence of signs

00:03:18.866 --> 00:03:21.912
and/or symptoms due to
an abnormal, excessive

00:03:21.912 --> 00:03:24.683
or synchronous neuronal
activity in the brain.

00:03:24.683 --> 00:03:26.675
This is what we spend
all of our time doing,

00:03:26.675 --> 00:03:29.150
looking at EEGs and videos to see

00:03:29.150 --> 00:03:30.535
what's the first thing that happened.

00:03:30.535 --> 00:03:31.568
Did the right arm move?

00:03:31.568 --> 00:03:32.537
Did the left arm move?

00:03:32.537 --> 00:03:34.079
Did the head turn to the side?

00:03:34.079 --> 00:03:35.331
'Cause that allows us to look back

00:03:35.331 --> 00:03:36.895
at our neuroanatomy and have some type

00:03:36.895 --> 00:03:38.555
of hypothesis as where that seizure

00:03:38.555 --> 00:03:40.206
is actually starting.

00:03:40.206 --> 00:03:41.855
As opposed to epilepsy.

00:03:41.855 --> 00:03:43.757
Again, this is debated and the definitions

00:03:43.757 --> 00:03:47.125
are changing, is still simply defined

00:03:47.125 --> 00:03:49.500
as two or more unprovoked seizures

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:51.547
greater than 24 hours apart.

00:03:51.547 --> 00:03:53.241
People debate this because what happens

00:03:53.241 --> 00:03:54.748
when someone has a seizure, and then

00:03:54.748 --> 00:03:56.575
five years later has their second seizure?

00:03:56.575 --> 00:03:59.391
Does that patient have epilepsy?

00:03:59.391 --> 00:04:01.964
Chief Justice John
Roberts, he has epilepsy

00:04:01.964 --> 00:04:03.700
'cause that's actually happened to him.

00:04:03.700 --> 00:04:05.450
I would say yes.

00:04:05.450 --> 00:04:07.123
Most of the patients that I treat,

00:04:07.123 --> 00:04:09.368
it doesn't become that nuanced because

00:04:09.368 --> 00:04:12.261
the kids are often
having frequent seizures.

00:04:12.261 --> 00:04:16.088
Then this is an expansion
of the definition.

00:04:16.088 --> 00:04:18.640
Having one unprovoked seizure.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:21.280
The probability of having a second seizure

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:23.240
being equivalent to if you already had

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:26.928
a second seizure, which is
generally around the 60%.

00:04:26.928 --> 00:04:29.786
There's a trend towards
actually giving someone

00:04:29.786 --> 00:04:32.424
a diagnosis of epilepsy at that point.

00:04:32.424 --> 00:04:34.933
Now, we can debate
whether or not we should

00:04:34.933 --> 00:04:37.749
actually intervene and start treating

00:04:37.749 --> 00:04:41.488
in that scenario of someone
who has a single seizure,

00:04:41.488 --> 00:04:44.812
has a high increased
risk of a second seizure.

00:04:44.812 --> 00:04:46.461
Do we actually treat?

00:04:46.461 --> 00:04:49.484
My personal practice is that I don't

00:04:49.484 --> 00:04:51.663
because we still don't know when

00:04:51.663 --> 00:04:53.280
that second seizure may be.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:54.578
The example that I just brought up,

00:04:54.578 --> 00:04:56.348
it may be five years.

00:04:56.348 --> 00:04:58.055
In that scenario, you've exposed someone

00:04:58.055 --> 00:05:01.606
to a medication for five
years unnecessarily.

00:05:01.606 --> 00:05:03.183
If it happens within the next few months,

00:05:03.183 --> 00:05:05.808
then I think it's
actually pretty clear that

00:05:05.808 --> 00:05:07.921
that tempo of having a
seizure every few months

00:05:07.921 --> 00:05:10.085
warrants intervention.

00:05:10.085 --> 00:05:11.870
Then diagnosis of an epilepsy syndrome.

00:05:11.870 --> 00:05:13.115
What is an epilepsy syndrome?

00:05:13.115 --> 00:05:15.782
This is the other academic topic

00:05:17.263 --> 00:05:18.635
that we get really excited about.

00:05:18.635 --> 00:05:20.925
If we can take someone that walks into

00:05:20.925 --> 00:05:24.015
our clinic with a diagnosis of spells,

00:05:24.015 --> 00:05:25.752
and then have them leave with a diagnosis

00:05:25.752 --> 00:05:27.237
of an epilepsy syndrome
so that they actually

00:05:27.237 --> 00:05:30.439
have a more specific label that they

00:05:30.439 --> 00:05:32.772
can put on their diagnosis,

00:05:33.814 --> 00:05:35.927
not only does that actually help inform

00:05:35.927 --> 00:05:39.520
treatment and prognosis,
but as I'll show you

00:05:39.520 --> 00:05:43.341
in a couple of slides,
I think it really helps

00:05:43.341 --> 00:05:45.790
families reach out to other

00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:47.938
disease-specific organizations so that

00:05:47.938 --> 00:05:49.105
they know that

00:05:50.458 --> 00:05:53.098
they can have support from other people

00:05:53.098 --> 00:05:55.167
who are dealing with
similar types of seizures

00:05:55.167 --> 00:05:57.039
and comorbidities.

00:05:57.039 --> 00:05:58.593
What is an epilepsy syndrome?

00:05:58.593 --> 00:06:00.876
It's a complex of signs and symptoms

00:06:00.876 --> 00:06:02.596
that define a unique epilepsy condition

00:06:02.596 --> 00:06:03.739
with different etiologies.

00:06:03.739 --> 00:06:05.815
The three pillars that go into determining

00:06:05.815 --> 00:06:09.020
the epilepsy syndrome
are the age of onset,

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:10.416
so very different if someone presents

00:06:10.416 --> 00:06:13.091
at six months of age as
opposed to six years of age,

00:06:13.091 --> 00:06:16.312
the seizure type and then the EEG pattern.

00:06:16.312 --> 00:06:18.477
Again, this is what we do in comprehensive

00:06:18.477 --> 00:06:20.689
epilepsy centers, is
rather than just giving

00:06:20.689 --> 00:06:22.803
someone the diagnosis of seizure disorder,

00:06:22.803 --> 00:06:24.624
which I hate that term, seizure disorder.

00:06:24.624 --> 00:06:25.475
It tells us nothing.

00:06:25.475 --> 00:06:27.301
People who have,

00:06:27.301 --> 00:06:28.993
don't have heart rhythm disorders, right?

00:06:28.993 --> 00:06:31.666
They have specific cardiac arrhythmias.

00:06:31.666 --> 00:06:34.945
We like to be able to be very accurate

00:06:34.945 --> 00:06:37.028
in our seizure diagnosis.

00:06:38.171 --> 00:06:39.784
Lastly, this term, semiology.

00:06:39.784 --> 00:06:41.952
I'm gonna show you a
few seizure videos here.

00:06:41.952 --> 00:06:44.669
The semiology are all of the nuances

00:06:44.669 --> 00:06:47.669
that happen prior, the onset, during

00:06:49.522 --> 00:06:51.556
and after the seizure that allow us

00:06:51.556 --> 00:06:55.723
to put a label, other than
generalized tonic-clonic.

00:06:56.956 --> 00:06:58.264
How about epilepsy in children

00:06:58.264 --> 00:07:00.301
with intellectual disability?

00:07:00.301 --> 00:07:01.974
This is an old paper,

00:07:01.974 --> 00:07:03.922
but epilepsy's common.

00:07:03.922 --> 00:07:05.559
Even in the general
population, it's estimated

00:07:05.559 --> 00:07:07.903
to be about 1% of the population.

00:07:07.903 --> 00:07:11.300
But it has a five-fold increase

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:14.039
in prevalence in those with
intellectual disability.

00:07:14.039 --> 00:07:15.680
When you look at the severity

00:07:15.680 --> 00:07:17.373
on intellectual disability, you can see

00:07:17.373 --> 00:07:20.310
there's a range here, but if one has mild

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:22.532
through the spectrum of
severe, the incidence

00:07:22.532 --> 00:07:24.388
of epilepsy does increase as the severity

00:07:24.388 --> 00:07:28.793
of the intellectual
disability also increases.

00:07:28.793 --> 00:07:29.904
Why?

00:07:29.904 --> 00:07:31.123
Why is that?

00:07:31.123 --> 00:07:34.073
Well, I don't think we actually know.

00:07:34.073 --> 00:07:35.953
I think the genetics here are, hopefully,

00:07:35.953 --> 00:07:37.777
gonna shed a little
bit more light on that.

00:07:37.777 --> 00:07:40.558
But when I explain this to parents,

00:07:40.558 --> 00:07:43.968
I basically say epilepsy
simply is a disorder

00:07:43.968 --> 00:07:45.737
of brain function.

00:07:45.737 --> 00:07:48.039
Development and cognition in a child,

00:07:48.039 --> 00:07:52.053
in a developing brain, rely
on normal brain function.

00:07:52.053 --> 00:07:56.484
Because development is
not a static process,

00:07:56.484 --> 00:07:58.919
you can imagine that someone who is prone

00:07:58.919 --> 00:08:00.446
to having seizures as a result of a

00:08:00.446 --> 00:08:02.748
functional disorder of
their brain may also

00:08:02.748 --> 00:08:06.915
be prone to having abnormal
development over time.

00:08:08.739 --> 00:08:11.173
This is one of the joys and frustrations

00:08:11.173 --> 00:08:12.006
of my job.

00:08:15.254 --> 00:08:16.939
Yes, adults, your brain is still changing,

00:08:16.939 --> 00:08:19.207
but hopefully we would
all agree, when we have

00:08:19.207 --> 00:08:22.088
a newborn that then becomes an infant

00:08:22.088 --> 00:08:25.356
and then a sassy teenager, a lotta stuff

00:08:25.356 --> 00:08:28.379
happens there in the brain.

00:08:28.379 --> 00:08:29.997
It is a moving target.

00:08:29.997 --> 00:08:32.067
We can have instances where there's either

00:08:32.067 --> 00:08:34.321
a genetic abnormality, a structural

00:08:34.321 --> 00:08:36.409
brain abnormality, that is present

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:38.832
in the newborn, period, but may actually

00:08:38.832 --> 00:08:41.109
not be symptomatic until later on.

00:08:41.109 --> 00:08:44.942
We have to be prepared
to re-evaluate children

00:08:46.188 --> 00:08:50.082
as they mature because their seizure types

00:08:50.082 --> 00:08:51.172
may change.

00:08:51.172 --> 00:08:54.011
That may actually dictate a
change in their treatment.

00:08:54.011 --> 00:08:55.615
Just a little vignette here.

00:08:55.615 --> 00:08:56.696
You have a child who comes in with

00:08:56.696 --> 00:08:58.247
new onset infantile spasms.

00:08:58.247 --> 00:08:59.668
I'm gonna show you a video of this.

00:08:59.668 --> 00:09:01.175
We do brain MRI, which is pretty much

00:09:01.175 --> 00:09:02.341
standard of care now.

00:09:02.341 --> 00:09:05.405
It shows a developmental
brain malformation.

00:09:05.405 --> 00:09:08.437
That patient is treated and does well.

00:09:08.437 --> 00:09:10.219
Spasms respond, and this
child is seizure free

00:09:10.219 --> 00:09:11.573
for a few years.

00:09:11.573 --> 00:09:13.385
But then later, that child develops

00:09:13.385 --> 00:09:16.148
a new type of seizure,
tonic and atonic seizures,

00:09:16.148 --> 00:09:17.687
which, again, I'm gonna show you.

00:09:17.687 --> 00:09:21.439
Now this is a diagnosis of
Lennox-Gastaut syndrome.

00:09:21.439 --> 00:09:23.166
Then we treat Lennox-Gastaut syndrome

00:09:23.166 --> 00:09:25.947
with very different types of medications.

00:09:25.947 --> 00:09:27.993
It's unusual to be able to get someone

00:09:27.993 --> 00:09:31.128
with Lennox-Gastaut
syndrome truly seizure free,

00:09:31.128 --> 00:09:33.249
but then as that child becomes an adult

00:09:33.249 --> 00:09:36.429
and ends up in my adult
epilepsy colleague's clinic,

00:09:36.429 --> 00:09:38.520
then they actually may just look like

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:42.635
they have treatment-resistant
complex partial seizures.

00:09:42.635 --> 00:09:44.801
I think my adult epilepsy colleagues

00:09:44.801 --> 00:09:46.640
have a really difficult job because

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:48.772
these patients show up.

00:09:48.772 --> 00:09:50.886
Unless you go back or they've come

00:09:50.886 --> 00:09:52.798
from their pediatric
colleagues and you have

00:09:52.798 --> 00:09:55.548
the nice longitudinal documentation

00:09:55.548 --> 00:09:58.465
of all the different
seizure types, you may not

00:09:58.465 --> 00:10:00.576
appropriately diagnose
someone in adulthood

00:10:00.576 --> 00:10:03.634
unless you go back and understand how

00:10:03.634 --> 00:10:06.052
their seizures presented
and how it evolved

00:10:06.052 --> 00:10:06.885
over time.

00:10:08.802 --> 00:10:10.112
Onto a few videos here.

00:10:10.112 --> 00:10:11.817
Infantile spasms.

00:10:11.817 --> 00:10:13.632
Here's a cute little baby.

00:10:13.632 --> 00:10:14.974
Let's just play this
video for those of you

00:10:14.974 --> 00:10:16.391
who haven't seen.

00:10:17.582 --> 00:10:20.211
What you'll see, awake,
alert, interactive,

00:10:20.211 --> 00:10:22.762
non-dysmorphic-appearing
baby who is starting

00:10:22.762 --> 00:10:26.635
